stylometry: The tradeoff between production cost and holding cost is that with production cost, you produce your product as orders come in, which can take longer orders and slow down the sales process. It also means you must have a staff on hand or at least the ability to produce at any time you may recieve an order. This generally means higher labor costs. You may have to rent a machine more than once also, and etc. Generally with this method you may keep up even with demand. With holding costs, you produce a predetemined amount and then pay for storage. You can create too much and have leftover product, or you can run out if demand is high and have to produce more product. Genreally labor costs are lower as production generally occurs all at once, however storage costs are now present.
